As before, this leaves horizontal domino 3 (3,1)-(3,2) uncovered. So, no. If we pick a different set, like (1,1), (2,1), (2,2). Then, vertical domino 7 (1,1)-(2,1) is covered, vertical domino 9 (1,3)-(2,3) not covered, etc. Not sure. Alternatively, (1,1), (1,2), (2,3). Then, horizontal domino 1 (1,1)-(1,2) is covered, horizontal domino 2 (2,2)-(2,3) not covered, etc. So, seems like 3 is insufficient. Therefore, the minimal number is 4. Therefore, the answer is \boxed{4}. **Final Answer** \boxed{4} </think> To determine the minimum number of guesses required to ensure that at least one of the guessed squares is covered by a hidden 2x1 rectangle on a 3x3 grid, we model the problem as a vertex cover in a bipartite graph.
